segments.text: Let's see.
The extracurricular student organizations, what were the big?
Well, again, I was limited in participation.
There were hometown clubs, they were very important.
And which one did you associate with?

I guess I went with San Antonio, and they met, but I, you know, I didn't, it wasn't any big deal, and then they had the Silent Solemn Club in the department, and again, I did participate some in them.
One of my, either my frustrations, or I don't know how it is, is that I had, I guess, wanted to participate in some of the judging programs, livestock judging teams, because that was a
high-level recognition to participate.
But I found it very incompatible with both the academic and work schedule because they just, it was kind of like band and football, it just took an inordinate amount of time.
I mean you were expected to practice three, two or three or four hours a day and then make a lot of weekend trips and everything.
And it was extremely time consuming and I took the courses out of which the teams were picked
But to make a commitment to go on the team, you tried out for it, it was so time consuming.
I think I qualified for one or two and then just decided it was just too much to handle.
I mean it was, if you're familiar with the livestock judging thing, it has, I think other than helping with your judgment, it's kind of like a debating thing.
You learn how to express yourself.
and have to be, you know... Who was, who was the academic advisor?
Do you remember?
Well, at the time it was Bill Warren, and he was a toughy.
You know, we're good friends now, and I remind him of this.

He had, he was fresh out of the Marines from World War II when he came here, and I guess may not have even had his doctorate by then, because at that time a lot of the professors didn't have their doctorate.
They had master's, maybe master's degree.
Anyway, he was
solid marine discipline, I mean, in his judging teams.

I don't know if that turned me off, but to this day he denies that he did that, but to shake you up when he wanted to be sure that the reasons that you gave, why you placed this animal over that, that you had solid reasons.
And if he didn't agree with you, he'd look you cold-bloodedly in the eye and say, you lied to me.
You know, you weren't consistent in what you said one time with him.
He said, he just looked you right in the eye and said, you lied to me.
But as I said, I consider him one of my good friends, and we'd laugh over that to this day.
He says he wouldn't have ever said that, but I know he did.
Now, what facilities were there for animal science across the tracks?
Nothing then.
It was all in the pavilion.
The judging was always, they brought the animals in.
And that was the coldest and the hottest place in the world.
At the old time, they used to, I remember freezing in there, they'd bring a,
Well, the usual way of judging for the teams was you'd get a class of four animals, four sheep, four horses, four kind of steers or whatever.
They'd bring them in, and you'd judge them there.
And the animal science building was all-inclusive.
It even had the meat laboratory in it.
It had everything in there, pretty much.
And then they had their farms across the track.
And you occasionally visited those as students.
They had a sheep farm, swine farm, beef camp, and so forth.
During all of your undergraduate years did you get to make any exotic trip as a part of the judging?
You didn't get to go to Kansas City?
No, I said I opted not to go with the Thames because it just took too much time.
And you know I've had nephews and others that have done this and even now our grandnieces and nephews are participating in that, but it was just too time consuming I thought.
And Dr. Butler, did you have any courses with him?
Yes, I did, and I can tell you a story on him that he denied to his...
He was a very emphatic teacher, and he had come out of the military, too, with some rank, I guess.
He was a Mitzvah person, taught Mitz.
And this is a true story, but he denies it to this day, as I told you, but he's passed away here recently.
But we had this...
situations, I told you, if you were in the upper 25% and made an A or B, you could exempt your final.
Well, that particular year, I don't know which it was, might have been my junior, I took the basic meets course, and I was tottering.

I was pushed for grades, and I was tottering between an A and a B, and I think the final counted a third, and I got to thinking, you know, I was computing my averages, that if I could almost max the final,
I could raise my grade.
But, you know, since my idea was to look at the final and decide, you know, if this isn't what I want to do, or I can't do it, I might as well not.
I guess one of the problems was, since it was sort of an optional thing, I really didn't study as hard as I should have.
Well, the final was a beast.
I mean, I looked at it and scanned through it, and I said, boy, I'm glad I'm exempt.
I started to leave.
And he said, I couldn't.
I made the option.
And I pulled my grade down to a C. And I never had forgiven him.
I must have really blown that thing.
He denies that.
But another thing, he was very emphatic.
He was one day, somebody asked him, you're familiar with the term jowl?
And he said, I don't know which way he said it.
He said, jowl.
And somebody said, is that the way you pronounce it?
And he said, of course.
I was trying to think of the word.
How?
He said, you know, rhymes with that.
Voice from the background, what about bowl?
He couldn't respond to that one.
He was put down for one time.
Did the student have a nickname for him?
No.
I remember another professor I shouldn't identify with.
Well, I guess it...
What was his name?
He taught sheep courses.
Dahlberg, Dahlberg.
He was kind of a laid-back type of professor, and I think some called him sleepy.
Anyway, one day I remember him coming into our class and just throwing his materials on the desk and obviously very unhappy.
He said he just came from Casey's, where people got coffee, and he said he overheard two students
standing in line there and one of them said, can I buy you a cup of coffee?
I said, no thanks.
They said, I'm going to Dahlberg's class and it may keep me awake.
Oh, that's a good one.
You're here four years as an undergraduate.
As you look back, to which faculty members would you give the highest marks that you, whose courses you had?
Well, Dr. Miller taught
I think a sheep course that I thought very highly of.
Tom Harrington I've mentioned.
And Bill Warren was a great teacher, don't get me wrong on that.
Bryson, Dr. Adrians, Dr. Bryson, these were people that stand out.
Fred Bryson?
Yeah.
People that I had courses under that stand out.
Which one was the toughest in terms of making the grade that you wanted?
the most demanding?
I don't really know.
That may be hard to point that out.
I might indicate what happened subsequently.
I mean, we're taking a lot of time on this particular part, but I'll just quickly thumbnail the rest of my career.
After the sophomore year, I did stay here for one summer, one semester.
I had the idea that since I was always carrying twenty to twenty-four hours I could graduate early and with the one to six hours in the summer maybe I could graduate early.
I was eager to get into the workforce and I worked here one, between my sophomore and junior year I went the first semester summer term and took some courses, a couple courses, which was a mistake.
You can't imagine how hot those dormitories are.

even with fans, they soak up the brick, and so forth, soaks up the heat, and it was really, and classes were hot too, even though they started at seven in the morning, but then I spent the rest of the summer working on the farm again, but I did, I was accumulating hours pretty fast, to the extent that I got my, qualified for my senior ring, I guess about a year or at least a semester ahead of my colleagues, and so that was a big achievement for me, and... How did you feel when you got that ring?
It's indescribable.
Anything after that would be anticlimactical.
Do you remember what it cost?
Thirty bucks, something like that, I think.
And did you earn it, or did your parents give it?
Well, I paid for it.
I mean, I'm pretty well paid for everything.
Have you ever lost it?
No, never.
And what about some interesting stories where somebody, some far, faraway place spotted it?
Oh, I've read about those.
But you've not had... No, I've never lost it.
I've never lost it.
And I don't wear it all the time.
I wear it when I'm out, but if I work in the yard or something, I don't wear it.
But it's pretty warm.
And I couldn't afford a diamond in it, of course.
I still don't have a diamond in it.
Okay, going on quickly.
A wonderful thing happened to me, as far as I was concerned, for my own career and future career.
About that time, they organized a new office of training program here, Army Security Agency.
I don't know if you've ever heard of that.
It's intelligence stuff.
And I guess it was a challenge.
If you were made to take an IQ test, and if you had a certain level of IQ, you were acceptable.
And at that time, there were only three schools offering the program, MIT, University of Illinois, and Texas A&M.
Hmm.
And so they organized a new unit, Army Security.
The first year, we weren't, enough of us, or there weren't any seniors, we were part of the signal company, because it was related to signal activities.
So we were juniors in the signal company.
But then my senior year, we became a company to ourselves, and it may be because of this academic thing,
We were the first one ever to win the George Moore Award.
Oh, really?
Yeah, this Army Security Agency.
But I said there was a kind of pre-selected group that went into that.
But I was really excited about getting into that program as an ROTC, and I made a commitment.
You had to make a commitment.
Of course, I needed the money, too.
At the end of your junior year, you had to decide whether you were going to get a contract, as they called it.
It was $21 a month, which was necessary, helpful.

and provided you additional uniforms, and of course that obligated you to take four years of the ROTC in that particular branch and do a summer camp, as you know, a six-week summer camp between your junior and senior year.
So that's what happened in the junior year.
I moved to Dormitory 11 the first year as part of the Signal Corps, and the next year we wore our own outfit.
Did that outfit have a nickname?
that intelligence outfit?
No, maybe behind our backs we did that.
We were part of a composite battalion.
I was, you know, from the background I had, any rank or achievement you made was highly honored.
I did make the battalion staff, I guess I became a captain as a senior, and
We were part of the composite staff, which included the specialized units like the signal core and chemical core.
Because I'm assuming that that outfit was kind of a scheme of the crop, wasn't it?
Well, it was because you had to take the IQ test to score a certain level on that.
I don't know, there were some interviews and things like that, but it was a selected group.
And we actually got to go to, during our summer camp, we went to Fort Meade and we actually went to...

what do they call those barracks out of Washington where this very famous code breaker during World War II visited with us and I can't think of his name but he was mostly involved in breaking codes and ciphers and it took I mean you've got these problems and they were you know like 400 crossword puzzles wrapped up into one because you had to you know study the frequency of the letters
try to figure out patterns.
And of course they've got machines to do all that nowadays.
And we hadn't started using machines then.
But I'm trying to think of the name of the barracks.
It's in the Pentagon area.
I mean, it was Arlington Farms.
Arlington Farms, I guess they called it.
It was kind of a secret area.
But we felt very well.
The other thing that happened my junior year, they started to reactivate the Ross Volunteers that year.
So I opted for that, which was time-consuming, but I liked the concept.
But we didn't do a whole lot because we were just getting organized.
How many were selected, as far as you recall, then?
Well, it was based on academics and... No, no, but how many students?
Well, it was a company.
There are pictures in there.
I would say in the books, I guess maybe 40 or 50.
I'm not sure.
And as far as you're aware, the selection of the RVs then was based on their
What were the factors?
I'm not sure.
I think academics entered into it, recommendations of your military ROTC instructors, these type of things.
And it was probably time consuming too, but I think we drilled about an hour a day most days.
And I had special roles to play in football games, but both during my junior and senior year, we didn't have all the fancy New Orleans trips.
The only exciting thing we did is during my senior year, we were the honor guard for the governor when we played the University of Texas over in Austin.
Who was the governor then?
Was this Coke Stevenson?
No, it was... Buford Jester?
Jester, that's who it was.
I think it was, yeah, I think it was.
And they described the uniform, make believe I'd never seen it.
Well, they've changed since then.
They got, I mean, it was very cheap.
It was white, but it was duck cloth.
like we used for cotton sacks.
Did it have the... Yeah, high collar, but it was a very, I mean, it only cost $20 or $25, but it was a cheap type of thing.
I'm sure they got, but it was part of the financial situation at the time, but it was a white uniform.
And we had the silver plated rifles, you know, that we played with and did the... And black shoes?
Probably, I don't know, I can't remember.
You know about the boot duration, how important that is.

Anyway, getting back to that, to finishing off my career, as I said, I had enough credits to graduate a semester early, but then I got committed to Army security, and I had to stay an extra semester to get my contract at the end of my second half of my senior year, which I really enjoyed because I had all my requirements except that,
So I jumped back and took all the courses I always wanted to take as electives and never had room for.
I always felt my education had not been complete because I never had had trigonometry in high school or in college, so I took trigonometry.
What else?
I can't remember all.
I took German because I had a little German background.
I thought, well, might as well take that.
I took a technical writing course because I took another option earlier than that.
And I think there were one or two animal science courses that weren't required that I took, but anyway.
Now, had German been spoken at home by your family?
To a limited extent.
It had been spoken at home pretty much.
I guess I knew German better than English when I started school.
In fact, I often get accused of not being Texan in my,

having English as a second language and with the grandparents and relatives who talked German but my parents made a real effort to talk English after I started school even though their English you know even till the day they died wasn't as good as it might have been I mean they had accents and so forth but they I mean about the time I started school English started they started speaking English all the time at home which was probably good for me but I
I always thought, well, I'd had that little start in it, and one of the reasons I selected it as one of my languages in the old days when you had to have languages for...
But that was a mistake, because I was in Wisconsin.
They had the toughest German department.
Oh, yeah.
And the French and the Spanish guys just breezed through it.
The German department wanted you really to be able to read, which was a shock.
They...
All right, now I kind of gather that this intelligence outfit was a spark to you.
Well, it was something we really enjoyed.
I mean, you felt you were somewhat as an elitist, I guess.
All right, by then, by the time you're taking those courses you really wanted to take that spring of your fourth year,
Had you zeroed in more surely on what you wanted to do?
Well, I was almost enamored with a military career by that time.

I mean, in fact, I had, I even had toyed with the idea of West Point somewhere along the line, either between my sophomore and junior year, and I started going in that direction until I had my ROTC physical here, and I found out I was nearsighted.
And at that time, West Point would not accept you unless you were 20-20.
I think they do now, I understand.
It's ridiculous.
It's easily correctable.
But I was told I would not be eligible, which, you know, I might have gone to a military career because I really got turned on by the military activity.
And he talked about professors.
There was a Major Jones assigned here who was the lone officer for Army Security.
He had been a signal officer but retraded as an Army Security because the work that Army Security did during the war had been done by the Signal Corps.
But it had gotten so important, code breaking and traffic analysis.
Are you familiar with that?
Communication, where you listen to radio and you position units where they are.
They call it order battle, all that.
They made a separate branch out of it, intelligence branch.
Anyway, I was really beginning to think in terms of a military career, and I guess I hadn't ruled it out.
And this Major Jones, I guess, gave me
the best advice I ever had.
I mean, he didn't particularly encourage, at that time, it was between the World War II and the Korean War, he encouraged my participation in the reserves.
He said, why don't you go civilian, you can still keep up your military interest.
And the conventional wisdom of the guys, my peers, don't get into the reserves.
Worst thing you could do, because you'll be the first to go.
And, uh,

But this guy gave me the best piece of advice, and he said, you know, from my perspective, at my age, he said, you ought to stay in there to earn the retirement benefits, because he said, you'll find that time will go on anyway.
And so I was one of the very few who opted for active reserve duty after I got my commission, which, unexpectedly,
kept me from having to go to Korea.
Because, you know, when a year after we graduated, I was already participating in reserve activities down at Fort Crockett in Galveston.
We'd have weekend trainings and things like that.
I remember being down there when the Korean War broke out.
And we were all expecting to be called immediately.
And that's what happened.
The ones who did not
commit to the reserves.
These were the guys that they called out, and they retraded them all as infantry officers.
They were platoon leaders.
In fact, I met a person who lives in this community who was in a subsequent, I think the following year, the people that graduated right at that time, I guess the class of 50, I was 49.
They were 36, I think he said.
No, maybe, it doesn't matter.
Anyway, at the time they got their commission
half were sent to Korea, half were sent to Germany.
And the half that were sent to Korea, there was not a single survivor.
These had been Army security people who had been retrented.
But I, in fact, my career was beginning to hinge on that, and my marriage and everything else, you know, I expected to go any time.
And they kept saying, you stay with the unit.
We'll call you as a unit when we want.
You'll probably be called.
And, you know, we kept, and it was that status.
It was down at El Campo where I belonged to a,

replacement unit and we in fact we were on call at least twice I mean alert and then they backed down on it for some reason or the other but I continued my reserve activities for 30 years and earned retirement benefits and Major Jones was right the time went on anyway.
Alright your senior spring describe final review
commencement for you and your family, your loved ones.
Wonderful experience.
Last semester was the first year at a time I really had fun because I was doing the courses I wanted and at that time too you know seniors were exempt, graduating seniors were exempt from finals.
That was nice.
You still want to make a good grade but you didn't have to worry about finals and particularly that week, I guess a week or so before last classes and
And graduation, that was really a fun week.
We could harass everybody else.
But I remember my senior review in a very interesting way.
We had the gosh awfulest downpour of rain you can ever imagine.
I can remember the guy with the bass horns pouring water.
Really?
I mean, it was absolutely monsoon rain the whole time.
Everybody got soaked to the,
And the graduation was in Caulfield, and everybody got pretty wet.
And I guess it was meaningful to me at that time, as graduation was commissioning, because I guess I was the first one from my community and family that ever got... Who came from your family?
My parents, I think, basically.
I think that was it, my parents.
Now, you hadn't met this special young lady yet?
No.
No.
No, that came later.
Your senior boots, where'd you get them and what'd you pay for them?
Oh, they were secondhand.
I got them from the boot shop.
Hollick's?
Hollick's, the boot shop, and they were secondhand and they never fit.
Any blisters?
Yeah, but I just wore them on ceremonial occasions, but it would have been nice if I could have, I think I probably paid $20 or $30 for them.
I think you ones were close, even at that time, close to $100.
Did you sell them back to them?
Oh, yes.
I probably bought what I paid for them, but they never did fit.
Anyway, I'll have to tell you one other story about the boots.

Of course, that's a very proud moment when you can put those boots on, and we were stupid enough or young enough, whatever you want, the 15 or 20 of us that were in this Army Security Unit were sent to Fort Meade, Maryland, so we could go to Washington, D.C. and participate and look at some of those intelligence activities.
Everybody else went to, I think, to...
I mean, the infantry, artillery people all went to like, what's the base in Oklahoma?
Fort Sill?
Fort Sill, or Port Hood, or some of those places, and we got to go to the exotic New York, or rather, Maryland.
My father had finally gotten a new car after the war.
It was just summer of 48.
and he was going to dump his old Hudson Terraplane.
And I said, well, let me have it.
So two colleagues of mine, one in Houston and one in San Antonio, the three of us drove to Maryland and participated at Fort Meade there.
And what I'm leading up to is we had the weekend two or three days off at 4th of July.
So we drove to New York City.
None of us had ever been out of state before.
And we wore our boots, of course.
We stayed, I think, five or six to a hotel room to cut down expenses.
And I remember two things.
Well, the main thing I remember was riding the boat out to the Statue of Liberty.
And, of course, there were a bunch of high school girls along there.
We found out they were from Brooklyn, and we gave them our attention, and they gave us their attention.
And one of them just finally couldn't contain herself.
She said, geez, what's with the boots?
Ha!
I said, this guy's talk's funny.
And that was very shocking to us.
All right.
As you graduated, what kind of world did you think you were entering?
And how well prepared did you think A&M had made you?
Well, I was, as I said, totally, I came back to my earlier commitment of wanting to be a county agent.
And I started working that pretty hard for my last year.
And it turned out that with all the veterans graduating and everything, they had a lot of candidates for jobs.
And I think they told me later for four, five, six openings they had, they had over 100 applicants.
But the Extension headquarters used to be in the Military Science Building.
Did you know that?
And then the Experiment Station was over here, what they call the Butler Building now.
All the Extension people were in one building, including the director and everybody else.
And I worked that very, very hard trying to be sure I'd get the position.
And one of the funnies that kind of reminds you of the military of putting you where you're least qualified, I remember filling out the application form.
And that stayed on the form a long time after.
There was a rule in extension service you couldn't work in your home county, which is probably a good rule, because you'd always be old man Jones' little kid.
But that was one rule.
You could work anywhere.
And I was filling out this form.
It was about a four-page form of a little background and everything.
Got the question, what part of the state would you prefer to work in?
And I, desperate for a job, I said, anywhere.
But I remember turning to the secretary and I said,
I put that on there, I said, but I hope they don't send me to the Rice area, because that's one thing I don't know anything about.
Uh-oh, uh-oh.
You know my first county.
The second county were both Rice counties.
Which county?
Wharton and, well, I was assistant agent in Wharton and county agent in Matagorda, Bay City.
When did that, when did you begin that?
Well, I graduated around the first of the,
June, as I recall.

I had my commission, I had my degree, and I had been selected for a training position, not a regular position, a training position in the Extension Service, and that was just kind of for you to get, until they had more openings and could observe you a little bit to see whether you'd fit the organization.
And I was, I remember working with the district supervisor who employed me for that job,
I wanted to go to work the week Monday after I graduated.
He said, look, take a week off at least.
You're never going to do it again.
Anyway, he talked me into that.
And I think it was on the 10th of June, I was sent as an agent in training, which was $2,600.
I'd have a car.
to work in, I guess they did that as a favor to me, to work in the neighboring county, Seguin, in Guadalupe County.
And there was a county agent there that I very much admired, Bill Rector, who was my first, and I only worked there about six weeks.
And then they transferred me as a training person to Beeville, Bee County.
And I worked, they were trying, the Extension Service was trying to get that county to put up the money for
an assistant position, and I started going in that direction.

But in September of that year I got a call from another supervisor from the Gulf Coast who had an opening in Wharton, a regular position, assistant county agent position in Wharton County, which was the Rice County.
And so I accepted that position, which was a regular position.
And, well, you can see it on there.
I worked in that position for
about a year and a half, and then I went to Michigan State because I felt my future would be enhanced in the extension service if I had gotten at least a master's degree.
And I also had subscribed to the notion that I didn't want to go directly into graduate school.
I thought it was good to get a little experience in between.
And I figured that after two years, usually at that time, if you successfully had about two years of assistant agent, you were ready for it.
agent position, I thought well if I'm ever going to get an education it would be better to do it between those two.
